[5] United Kingdom (Devon)
Date: 10 May 2015
Source: West Briton [abridged, edited]
http://www.westbriton.co.uk/Measles-outbreak-sweeps-Devon/story-26473977-detail/story.html


An outbreak of measles in the local community has prompted health experts to encourage parents to get their children vaccinated against the disease. Public Health England (PHE) is asking parents to take their children to the GP to get the measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) jab following the confirmed outbreak in Devon. PHE has confirmed 2 cases of measles in the Ashburton area (just 25 miles from the Cornwall border) and 3 other suspected cases in the local area.

Letters have been issued to parents at local schools advising them that measles is circulating in the community and to ensure their children are fully protected against the condition by having 2 doses of the MMR vaccine.

Dr Nick Young, consultant in communicable disease control for Public Health England in Devon, Cornwall and Somerset, said: "While most people who catch measles will recover completely within a couple of weeks, it's important to remember measles can be a very serious illness that can leave permanent disability, and occasionally even kill. "I'd appeal to any parents who have not yet had their children vaccinated to get them protected as soon as possible through their GP. Children should receive 2 doses of MMR vaccine for maximum protection, MMR not only protects them, but also limits the chances of the virus spreading more widely, for example to children who are too young to have the vaccine and to adults who may be more vulnerable to the disease. It is important to remember that MMR is a highly effective and safe vaccine."

Two doses of the MMR vaccine offer full protection against the 3 illnesses, provided the 1st dose is given after 12 months of age and the 2nd after 18 months of age. Unless advised otherwise, parents should follow the recommended NHS vaccination schedule. The vaccine may also protect children if given within 72 hours of exposure to someone with measles. If already infected with measles, the MMR will not cause any harm.

